{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UXT7dpaFkaiaYN53eaokh6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the precondition set up two transport CA secrets and a CA bundle configmap. The configmap initially only has ca1.crt (one certificate). The stage is about \"elasticsearch-cert-ingress-tighten\", and specifically the \"transport_ca_fault_replant\" precondition.\n\nLooking at the precondition more carefully:\n1. It checks if the ca-bundle configmap has only 1 certificate (`n=\"1\"`)\n2. It creates secrets es-transport-ca1 and es-transport-ca2\n3. It creates a configmap es-transport-ca-bundle with only ca1.crt\n4. It attempts to delete a pod es-cluster-2 that doesn't actually exist\n\nThe fault scenario appears to be that the cluster has two CA certificates available, but the ca-bundle configmap only contains the first one. This means elasticsearch-2's transport certificate, which is signed by ca2, wouldn't be trusted by the other nodes. Yet the cluster is showing all 3 nodes running and green status, so I need to look more closely at how the StatefulSet is actually configured.\n\nLooking at the probe logic again, it checks if the ca-bundle has exactly 1 certificate—that's the fault condition. When the bundle already has both CAs, the probe passes and triggers the apply, which resets it back to just ca1. Then it tries to delete the non-existent es-cluster-2 pod. This suggests the StatefulSet might be mounting this configmap, so I should examine that configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1646,"cache_read_input_tokens":31523,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1646},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6e7698f5-9219-4f73-b5a6